{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YZTgbi463FUEM5caGx4wkj","type":"tool_result","content":"33-\n34-1. **A declarative workflow engine** that drives multi-agent execution. A YAML workflow definition specifies task states, transitions, per-task prompts, agent assignments, expected inputs/outputs, and session boundaries (fresh context vs. continuation). This replaces Ralph's 1000+ lines of bash orchestration with something configurable and clean. Execution uses the Claude Agent SDK (`@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk`) — the official TypeScript API for programmatic Claude Code control.\n35-\n36-2. **A single adversarial verification pass** against the final built artifact. No per-story micro-verification. No session flags. No proof document regex parsing. One blind evaluator agent — no source code access, only Docker, observability, and documentation — exercises the final artifact subjectively and produces a structured JSON verdict. The evaluator reads ACs in user language and independently figures out how to test them.\n37-\n38:3. **A multi-level agent and workflow configuration system.** Agents and workflows exist at three levels: embedded (ships with codeharness), user-level, and project-level — with hybrid patching to customize without replacing. 9 embedded agents (8 BMAD + evaluator) and 1 default workflow ship out of the box. Agent personality uses BMAD-compatible fields as the base with optional PersonaNexus-compatible traits for fine-grained behavioral tuning.\n39-\n40-BMAD owns planning (briefs, PRDs, architecture, stories). Codeharness owns execution and verification — taking BMAD's output and driving it to a proven-working artifact.\n41-\n42-### What Makes This Special\n43-\n44-- **Declarative, not imperative.** Workflow YAML defines agent dispatch, session control, and handoff contracts. No more reading bash to understand what happens next.\n45-- **Honest verification.** One blind evaluator at the end, exercising the real artifact subjectively. The verifier can't see source, can't be fooled by passing tests, can't talk itself into approval. Structured JSON evidence required for every AC verdict.\n46:- **Configurable everything.** Agents and workflows are configurable at embedded, user, and project levels. Patch any embedded agent or workflow without replacing it — override specific fields or append to prompts.\n47-- **Agent-as-assignee with structured personality.** Tasks are assigned to specific agents with BMAD personas and optional quantified personality traits (warmth, rigor, directness, etc.). The evaluator is tuned for high rigor and zero leniency.\n48-- **Aggressive legacy removal.** The 4-format proof parser, session flags, self-verification path, per-story hooks, and hardcoded Ralph logic all get deleted. Only clean code survives.\n49-\n50-### Project Classification\n51-\n--\n104-6. Evaluator finding injection into retry prompts\n105-7. Score-based circuit breaker (replaces file-change counting)\n106-8. Trace ID generation and injection per iteration\n107-9. Multi-level agent configuration (embedded/user/project) with hybrid patching\n108-10. Multi-level workflow configuration (embedded/user/project) with hybrid patching\n109:11. 9 embedded agents (8 BMAD + evaluator) and 1 default embedded workflow\n110-12. Issue tracking via `issues.yaml` — replaces beads, retro findings auto-added, engine executes issues alongside stories\n111-13. Legacy deletion (Ralph bash, session flags, proof parsers, self-verify hooks, beads)\n112-14. Unit tests for all new modules (80%+ coverage)\n113-\n114-### Growth (Phase 2)\n--\n130-\n131-**Evaluator quality:** Anthropic found that \"out of the box, Claude is a poor QA agent.\" The evaluator judges subjectively — it reads ACs and independently exercises the artifact, requiring evidence for every verdict. **Mitigation:** Structured JSON output forces evidence. Calibrate against known-broken artifacts. Log all evaluator sessions. Run multiple trials (pass^3 is the real metric). Iterate on the evaluator prompt across real projects.\n132-\n133-**Legacy removal scope:** Deleting Ralph, hooks, and verification paths simultaneously is a big bang. **Mitigation:** Build the new engine alongside the old code. Switch over when the new engine passes the same test suite. Then delete.\n134-\n135:**Solo developer:** One person doing engine + evaluator + config system + legacy removal + tests. **Mitigation:** The agents do the implementation work. Codeharness v2 is the first real test of codeharness v2.\n136-\n137-## User Journeys\n138-\n139-### Journey 1: First Run (Happy Path)\n140-\n--\n193-\n194-### Journey 4: Broken Environment\n195-\n196-Alex runs `codeharness init` on a machine without Docker installed. The CLI detects the missing dependency and reports: \"Docker not found — required for blind evaluator verification. Install Docker Desktop and re-run init.\"\n197-\n198:Alex installs Docker but has no BMAD project set up. `codeharness init` reports: \"No BMAD agent configs found at `_bmad/bmm/agents/`. Run BMAD setup first, or use `--skip-bmad` to use only embedded agents.\"\n199-\n200:Alex uses `--skip-bmad`. Init succeeds with embedded agents only. Later, `codeharness run` completes stories but the evaluator fails — Docker daemon isn't running. Engine reports: \"Evaluator spawn failed: Docker daemon not running. Verdict: UNKNOWN for all ACs. Start Docker and resume with `codeharness run --resume`.\"\n201-\n202-Alex starts Docker, runs `--resume`. Engine picks up from the verify step, evaluator exercises the artifact. Done.\n203-\n204-### Journey 5: Retro Findings → Issues → Implementation\n205-\n--\n285-\n286-### Multi-Level Configuration\n287-\n288-```\n289-# Embedded (inside codeharness package)\n290:templates/agents/     # 8 BMAD + evaluator\n291-templates/workflows/  # default sprint workflow\n292-\n293-# User-level\n294-~/.codeharness/agents/      # personal agent customizations\n295-~/.codeharness/workflows/   # personal workflows\n--\n333-- FR5: System validates workflow YAML against a JSON schema at parse time and rejects malformed definitions\n334-- FR6: System ships a default embedded workflow that handles standard BMAD sprint execution without user customization\n335-\n336-### Agent Configuration\n337-\n338:- FR7: System ships 9 embedded agents: dev, qa, architect, pm, sm, analyst, ux-designer, tech-writer, evaluator\n339-- FR8: User can create custom agents at project level (`.codeharness/agents/`) or user level (`~/.codeharness/agents/`)\n340-- FR9: User can patch embedded or user-level agents via `extends:` with structured `overrides:` and freeform `prompt_patches:`\n341:- FR10: Agent config supports BMAD-compatible base fields (name, role, persona with identity/communication_style/principles) and optional PersonaNexus-compatible traits (10 dimensions, 0-1 scale)\n342-- FR11: System resolves agent config through embedded → user → project patch chain at runtime\n343-- FR12: System compiles resolved agent config into Claude Code inline subagent definition for SDK dispatch\n344-\n345-### Workflow Configuration\n346-\n--\n417-- NFR5: `codeharness status` returns in <1s regardless of run history size\n418-\n419-### Reliability\n420-\n421-- NFR6: Engine state survives process crashes — on restart, execution resumes from the last completed task\n422:- NFR7: Evaluator session timeout does not crash the engine — timeout is a scored failure, not a fatal error\n423-- NFR8: All engine state is persisted to disk after each task completion\n424-- NFR9: Engine handles programmatic agent dispatch API errors gracefully (API limits, network failures) with specific error reporting\n425:- NFR10: Long-running executions (4+ hours) do not degrade in correctness or accumulate resource leaks\n426-\n427-### Integration\n428-\n429-- NFR11: Engine uses the official programmatic agent dispatch API — no direct CLI process spawning\n430-- NFR12: BMAD agent configs are read-only — engine never modifies agent YAML files"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_013RkPud9KrEYQUqFbUbV1H1","session_id":"87824d62-8d3a-42e8-9563-dae1782fbf60","uuid":"f8de013a-9434-40a8-bb1c-8fadd3ca0a7b","timestamp":"2026-04-02T15:32:59.774Z"}
